{
  "lesson_id": "lesson_auxiliary_ta",
  "lesson_title": "The Marker of Completion: Auxiliary た (ta)",
  "lesson_summary": "Having explored the past of personal memory (ki) and hearsay (keri), we now examine 'ta'—the auxiliary that signals an action is fully completed and its result remains.",
  "grammar_point": "auxiliary_ta",
  "grammar_explanation": {
    "concept": "The auxiliary 'ta' (た) functions similarly to the Chinese aspect marker '了' (le). While 'ki' and 'keri' focus on the 'pastness' of an event, 'ta' emphasizes the completion of the act or the state that exists because the act finished.",
    "formation": "Attached to the Ren'yokei (Continuative form) of verbs. In classical texts, it often appears as a contraction of 'te-ari' (has become/is in the state of).",
    "variations": [
      "tari (the uncontracted formal version)",
      "te (the conjunctive form often preceding it)"
    ],
    "common_confusions": [
      "vs. ki (き): 'ki' is for things you personally remember; 'ta' is for the objective fact of completion.",
      "vs. keri (けり): 'keri' is for realization or hearsay; 'ta' is more direct and factual."
    ]
  },
  "teaching_sequence": [
    {
      "type": "introduction",
      "content": "In previous lessons, we looked at how classical poets recall the past through the lens of memory (ki) or sudden realization (keri). However, sometimes a poet simply needs to state that an action is *finished*—the logical 'done' state. This is where 'ta' (た) comes in. Think of it as the 'Completion Tag.' If 'ki' is 'I remember crossing,' 'ta' is 'I have crossed (and am now on the other side).'"
    },
